The Stipulation looks fine, with the understanding you wish to hold the election sooner rather than later. As we
have discussed, drivers can often be more readily swayed when given more time to think about the decision (which
is largely why the unions pushed so heavily for the new ???quickie??? election rules in the first place). An
additional week would likely be enough.
To the extent the election remains the 24th, the following dates are important:
?? Today: sign the stipulation (and tomorrow???s hearing will therefore be canceled).
?? Friday: email the list of voters (including their name, job class, shift, address, and if the company already
has it, their cell phones and email addresses) to both the Board agent and the Union???s attorney
Sunday before midnight: Post the Election Notice at the facility.
Tuesday (Sept. 22) before midnight: hold the last group meeting
Wednesday (Sept. 23): choose an election observer who is a non-management employee, typically a
receptionist, bookkeeper, payroll clerk, etc. I can provide training materials for the observer???s duties.
Thursday (Sept. 24) at 5:30 a.m. appear for the pre-election conference, where the election procedures will
be discussed by the Board agent. I can walk you through the procedures, and if you wish, I can have
someone from the firm???s LA office appear for the pre-election conference.
Finally, we discussed some campaigning and communications that may be worth pursuing. It may even be
worthwhile to call an outsider (LRI) in to hold a meeting with employees on the dangers of unionization. I would be
happy to provide some materials for you. Please contact me after you have reviewed the above with any
